    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x0": "Hallucination in A: 'until his death on 11 April 1945' — source doesn't state he died. F has highest information density without hallucination. All candidates cover the key entities well. B and C's source attribution footnotes are a nice touch for traceability.",
    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x1": "E has the best coverage-to-hallucination ratio—mentions mass arrests, camp transfers, and resistance without over-claiming. F hallucinates (Auschwitz link, perpetrator speculation). B is conservative but complete. D mentions 'nearly 2,000' which is a valid inference.",
    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x2": "D is the best summary—covers all quantitative details, captures the 'disparate group' framing, and avoids hallucination. First-person candidates are a stylistic choice, not an error per se, but they change the register. All maintain good factual coverage.",
    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x3": "C is the most complete summary—covers the Kommandant's declaration, the September transports, and the anti-fascist resistance arc. F has the 'Buchananwald' error. E is decent but slightly confused on the Kommandant's orders.",
    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x4": "D is the strongest—highest information density, good hedging, no hallucinations. C adds 'night' which is a minor hallucination. All candidates handle the core narrative well. F is concise but drops some important nuance (the 'pariah' status)."
